com.wm.xmldata

Class XmlDataAnyTag

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataTag
      • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataContentTag
        • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataAnyTag
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable

    public class XmlDataAnyTag
extends XmlDataContentTag
    The XmlDataAnyTag class constructs an XmlData any-tag from its constituent parts. There are methods that return the full-name as well as the path-name. The full-name is used in XmlData infosets and is always paired with an any-item and the pair is a member of a group-value The path-name is used in map-paths and copy-paths; they contains additional qualifying information.

    The any-tag full-name format is: 

         {particle-id}*any
    where the particle-id identifies the position of this any-tag relative to all any-tags in a content model. For example, a content model might employ a wildcards in the first and fourth position, with other elements in the second and third positions. 
         {1}*any    signifies the first occurrence and
     {2}*any    signifies the second occurrence of a wildcard in the model

    The any-tag path-name format is 

         {particle-id}*any[index]{}indirect-qualifier}
    It includes additional properties: index specifies an offset into an array of repeating any-items and indirect-qualifier specifies the value-tag for indirect-items.

    For exapmple, the 5th repeating value of the 3rd any-tag with a value-tag is: 

         {3}*any[4]{able#sample.org}

    • Method Detail

      • createFromPath

        public static XmlDataAnyTag createFromPath(java.lang.String name,
                                           XmlNamespaceMap nsDecls)
        Create an XmlDataAnyTag from its String representation. Its form is {particleId}*any[index][indirectQualifier}
        where:
        • particleId -- the particle-id
        • index -- the value index (starting at 0 or a symbolic iterator
        • indirectQualifier -- is the indirect-item value tag or an iterator-tag
        If particleId is omitted, it defaults to {1}. The index and qualifier never appear in the instance tag; they are used only in the tag to provide additional information to methods. If particleId is omitted, it defaults to {1}. There is no default for index or qualifier; when not specified, such tags are unindexed and unqualified. Examples: 
           {3}any
   *any[!v]
   *any[3]{info#example.org}
   {1}*any[2]{!x}
        Parameters:
        name - the full name of the Tag as used in a path
        nsDecls - the namespace declaration
        Returns:
        an XmlDataAnyTag
